	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Africa urged to diversify and structurally transform</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The ‘Africa Progress Report 2011’, prepared by the Africa Progress Panel, chaired by Kofi Annan, was released and presented to the World Economic Forum meeting in Cape Town on 5 May 2011. The report observes that ‘the emergence of non-European trade partners, notably China, has not changed the fact that the continent mainly exports raw materials and imports manufactured goods’. Indeed, the pattern is becoming ‘ever more entrenched’. The Africa Progress Report argues that economic growth needs to be ‘accompanied by much-needed structural transformation and diversification’. It is maintained that ‘the lack of diversification in products and partners made African trade volatile and explains why the continent’s GDP growth has not translated into tangible improvement in people’s lives.’ The report urges African governments to ‘speed up economic diversification’. This, it argues, requires the adoption of measures ‘targeting the informal sector, easing labour rigidities, improving infrastructure, and promoting regional integration’.</p><p>Efforts meanwhile are under way to strengthen Malawi’s economic relations with India in sectors as diverse as agriculture, telecommunications and pharmaceuticals. While current discussions are focusing on a US$800m factory for producing HIV/AIDS drugs and equipping a computerised taxation system, market opportunities for a range of agricultural exports are also being explored. This includes export opportunities for ‘pigeon peas’, for which there is a big market in India.</p><p>China for its part signed an accreditation agreement with the East African Community in May 2011, a move which is taken as a sign of China’s growing commercial interest in the region. According to World Bank estimates, ‘East Africa will receive new investments in excess of US$25 billion in the next five years’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>Creamer Media’s Engineering News online</i> (Johannesburg), ‘Africa failing to changer harmful trade patterns – report’, 6 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;news_id=103133&amp;cause_id=1694" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;news_...</a><br />
IPS, ‘Malawians keen to build trade ties with India’, 10 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=55565" target="_self">http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=55565</a><br />
<i>Business Daily </i>(Nairobi), ‘China’s tighter ties with EAC signal new scramble for regional business’, 10 May 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause_id=1694&amp;news_id=103343&amp;cat_id=1026" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The need to ensure that economic growth promotes ‘much-needed structural transformation and diversification’ raises important issues related to the underlying trajectory for reform of the EU’s CAP. The reformed CAP places far greater emphasis on the competitive production of value-added food products within the EU for both EU and international markets, and a reduced emphasis on exports of undifferentiated bulk agricultural commodities. However the question arises as to whether such a policy orientation will <i>de facto</i> reduce opportunities for ACP countries which wish to move their production up food and agricultural value chains, in order to produce a higher percentage of value-added products for national, regional and international markets.</p><p>This directly relates to the EPA negotiations and the issue of the removal of the non-tariff barriers (e.g. infant industry protection) to EU exports of value-added food products. This needs to be seen in the light of the extensive use of traditional trade-policy tools by the EU in the management of trade in sensitive agricultural products (these range from the inclusion of TRQs in trade agreements to the continuation of minimum import price arrangements).</p><p>Looking beyond the EU, how can China’s growing interest in the eastern and southern Africa region be capitalised on to foster investment in value-added processing in food and agricultural supply chains? For example, could China’s growing interest in high quality arabica coffees be used to leverage investment in greater local roasting and packaging of arabica coffee produced in the eastern African region?</p>
		</div>
		
